« Symphony of An Immigrant »

A new path is uncomfortable and might take longer than you expect. The Debut’s Symphony of violinist Scott Tixier is a tribute to his journey as an immigrant. Thrown into a new world without a net or a plan B. It’s leaving everything behind in pursuit of something extraordinary. Against the logic, the reason, in intent to be completely free. It develops in three movements. 

The opening and first movement represent the inevitable and impulsive nature of moving to a new continent. Hostile and unfamiliar at first, but full of excitement and mysteries to unfold. 

The second movement is an ode to what was once home but is no longer. Trying to navigate nostalgia and building new memories in that new environment. An internal struggle between past and present.

It closes with the 3rd movement unleashing the hope of a new beginning while looking at the path that has been traveled—a retrospective of one journey through the accomplishments, sorrows, scares, and trophies. 

Everyone has a singular and unique story, “The Symphony of An Immigrant” is to celebrate all that have left their home, literally or metaphysically. For the ones that are right now, away from their roots, and for those that are building new ones. »

What’s your favorite part of being an artist?

Freedom. I’m free. I do whatever I want with my energy and each time I do something, it’s something that makes me grow and something that makes me feel alive. I’m not working for anyone for anything–I like to be free. 

It’s a long journey, but when you improvise, you learn how to let go, to be in the moment, in the present, not think about the future, not think about the past. You’re right there right now with the music and you’re in the zone. That’s a privilege. That’s one of my favorite things, the essence of it is being freed, and freeing others.

It's easy to judge ourselves for things we didn't achieve or things that went wrong and forget how much we've grown. Some of you might have had the darkest days of your life, you may be overwhelmed with challenges that seem impossible. You may be dealing with grief and trauma. I know I certainly did! In 2018 my entire world was crushed, It seemed impossible to survive it, I couldn't breathe. This was the darkest time of my life. Going to therapy was helpful but time has proven to be my best friend. Time and being kind to yourself is an incredible practice that you can learn to use... I did not mean for this post to be an Instagram motivational thing but if you are in this situation right now, know that there is light at the end, it might take longer than you want but it will get better and great things will come to you, be kind to yourself, even if you have a hard time to be, trying is already a win!

Seventeen years of life in the United States, leaving behind France had led me to this pivotal point – my naturalization interview.

Inside, a palpable sense of purpose surrounded fellow applicants, each on their unique journey. Carrying photographs and memories, I felt the weight of my transformation as I entered the interview room. Questions flowed, testing my connection to this country and its history.

Memories flashed by – the first steps on American soil, friendships formed, challenges overcome. Each answer I gave echoed years of resilience and adaptation. Then, a smile from the immigration officer and the words I longed for: "Congratulations, you have passed the naturalization test." Tears welled up – relief and joy intermingled. Emerging from the building, the papers in hand, captured by my friend Will. @willvonbolton 

As I walked forward, I carried the story of an immigrant, now ready to not only embrace my new rights but also shape the future – one vote at a time.

🎥 - @willvonbolton

May 1st, 1996, my twin brother and I took a stand against racism, discrimination, and unemployment in France. Our first protest for equity and social justice. I remember crafting that protest sign right before the strike 🪧 - the way that old pic got colorized is taking me back in the 90s 🤯

Today, I stand before you with a heart full of gratitude, my journey rooted in a love for jazz music in America. This moment isn't just about gaining citizenship; it's the culmination of years marked by challenges, sacrifices, and unwavering determination to forge a new life in a foreign land.
 
As I look back on the years that have brought me to this very moment, I am reminded of the young, hopeful soul who arrived in this country with nothing but dreams and aspirations. I remember the feeling of isolation, of being in an unfamiliar place with no landmarks to guide me, no family to lean on, and no financial safety net to catch me if I fell. But it was precisely in those moments of uncertainty that I discovered the strength within me – a strength that would carry me through every hurdle that lay ahead.
 
The road to becoming an American citizen was not an easy one. 17 long years! It was paved with countless obstacles and pushed me to my limits. I navigated a labyrinth of legal complexities in a maze of paperwork and regulations. I can recount the restless nights poring over forms, the daunting immigration interviews, and the persistent battles against doubt and fear.
 
Today, as I stand here as a newly American citizen, I am overwhelmed by a mix of emotions. There's the satisfaction of achievement, the relief of knowing that the years of uncertainty and precariousness are behind me. There's the joy of knowing that the sacrifices made by myself and those who supported me were not in vain. 
 
My journey has shown me the power of resilience, the value of determination, and the beauty of unity in diversity.
 
In closing, let us remember that the challenges we overcome, the sacrifices we make, and the dreams we chase are what shape us as individuals. As I embark on this new chapter of my life, I do so with a heart full of hope, a spirit filled with gratitude, and an unwavering dedication to contributing my part to the American story.
 
Warmly,
Scott Tixier

I want to share something important with my community and followers during Color Blind Awareness Month. I'm color blind, and though I shouldn't feel weird about it, I often do. As a kid, I realized I couldn't see red the same way as everyone else, which made simple tasks like using a red chalkboard at school or picking strawberries embarrassing. But it's crucial to remember that 1 out of 12 males is colorblind, and some notable figures like Keanu Reeves, Mark Zuckerberg, Bill Clinton, and even Vincent Van Gogh shared this condition. You're not alone, and it's time to embrace our unique perspective on the world. Discovering @enchroma glasses has been a life-changing experience for me. At 37 years old, I witnessed the breathtaking beauty of a sunset with all its shades and nuances, and I saw a rainbow in its full spectrum for the very first time. The emotions overwhelmed me, and I couldn't stop crying tears of joy. These glasses have allowed me to see the world like never before, and I'm excited to share this incredible journey during Color Blind Awareness Month.

It’s been a privilege to be involved in @jonbatiste and @suleikajaouad remarkable story. I first met Jon 16 years ago when I just arrived in New York. We shared rides on the A train, heading to jam sessions in Harlem. Today, a @netflix documentary showcases Jon composing a symphony during a challenging period, as his life partner, writer Suleika Jaouad, faces a resurgence of her cancer. This film captures a moment of convergence for two creative souls, delving into themes of art, affection, and the artistic journey. Being part of this project, performing in his symphony, is an incredible experience. Merci beaucoup!✨🎻
